catalogue.definition: Identification of the radar station from which the data are received.
catalogue.remark:
Note:
    The defined SACs are on the EUROCONTROL ASTERIX website
    (www.eurocontrol.int/asterix)
catalogue.title: Data Source Identifier

catalogue.definition: Type and characteristics of the radar data as transmitted by a radar station.
catalogue.remark:
Note:

    - Bit-7 (SIM) is used to identify a simulated target report as produced by a traffic simulator.
catalogue.title: Target Report Descriptor

items.name: SSRPSR
items.title: Radar Detection in Last Antenna Scan

values: Plot or track from a fixed transponder

items.name: DS1DS2
items.title: Radar Detection in Last Antenna Scan

catalogue.definition:
Warning/error conditions detected by a radar station for the target
report involved.
catalogue.remark:
Notes:

    1. Warning/error condition values 0-63 are reserved for common
       standard use, whereas the values 64-127 are application dependent.
catalogue.title: Warning/Error Conditions

values: Possible wrong altitude information, transmitted when the Code C credibility check fails together with the Mode-C code in binary notation

catalogue.definition: Measured position of an aircraft in local polar co-ordinates.
catalogue.remark:
Note:

    - When expressed in 16 bits, signed or unsigned azimuths have the same value.
catalogue.title: Measured Position in Polar Co-ordinates

catalogue.definition: Calculated position of an aircraft in Cartesian co-ordinates.
catalogue.remark:
Notes:

    1. LSB is calculated as :math:`2^{-6+f}`.
    2. A default quantisation unit of 1/64 NM is obtained for a value of f = 0.
    3. Negative values are expressed in 2's complement form, bit-32 and
       bit-16 shall be set to 0 for positive values and 1 for negative values.
catalogue.title: Calculated Position in Cartesian Co-ordinates

catalogue.definition: Reply to Mode-2 interrogation.
catalogue.remark:
Notes:

    1. Smoothed Mode-2 data (bit-14 set to one) is used when the plot
       contains no Mode-2 code or the Mode-2 codes of the plot and track
       are different.
    2. Bits-16/15 have no meaning in the case of a smoothed Mode-2 and
       are set to 0 for a calculated track.
catalogue.title: Mode-2 Code in Octal Representation

values: Mode-2 code as derived from the reply of the transponder
Smoothed Mode-2 code as provided by a local tracker

catalogue.definition: Confidence level for each bit of a Mode-2 reply as provided by a monopulse SSR station.
catalogue.remark:
Note:
    - This Data Item is only transmitted if at least one pulse is of low quality.
catalogue.title: Mode-2 Code Confidence Indicator

catalogue.definition: Mode-3/A code converted into octal representation.
catalogue.remark:
Notes:

    1. The detector signals a garbled code (bit-15 set to one) when at
       least two replies are overlapping.
    2. Smoothed Mode-3/A data (bit-14 set to a one) are used in the case
       of the absence of Mode-3/A code information in the plot, or in the
       case of a difference between the plot and track Mode-3/A code information.
    3. Bits-16/15 have no meaning in the case of a smoothed Mode-3/A and
       are set to 0 for a calculated track.
catalogue.title: Mode-3/A Code in Octal Representation

values: Mode-3/A code derived from the reply of the transponder
Smoothed Mode-3/A code as provided by a local tracker

catalogue.definition: Confidence level for each bit of a Mode-3/A reply as provided by a monopulse SSR station.
catalogue.title: Mode-3/A Code Confidence Indicator

catalogue.definition: Mode-C height converted into binary representation.
catalogue.remark:
Notes:

    1. The detector signals a garbled code when at least two replies are overlapping.
    2. The maximum height which can be represented is 204 775 ft.
       Practically the maximum valid value is 126 750 ft (refer to ICAO Annex 10).
    3. Negative values are expressed in 2's complement form, bit-14 is
       set to 0 for positive values and 1 for negative values.
catalogue.title: Mode-C Code in Binary Representation

catalogue.definition:
Mode-C height in Gray notation as received from the transponder together
with the confidence level for each reply bit as provided by a monopulse SSR station.
catalogue.remark:
Notes:

    1. This Data Item is only transmitted if at least one pulse is of low quality.
    2. The detector signals a garbled code when at least two replies are overlapping.
catalogue.title: Mode-C Code and Code Confidence Indicator

catalogue.definition: Radial component of the ground speed as measured by means of Doppler filter banks in radar signal processors.
catalogue.remark:
Notes:
    1. LSB is calculated as :math:`2^{-14+f}`.
    2. A default quantisation unit of 14.0625 kt and a maximum of +/- 1 800 kt
       is obtained for a value of f = 6.
    3. Negative values are expressed in 2's complement form, bit-8 is
       set to 0 for positive values and 1 for negative values.
catalogue.title: Measured Radial Doppler Speed

catalogue.definition: Additional information on the quality of the target report.
catalogue.remark:
Notes:
    - The actual meaning of the bits is application dependent."

    - This Data Item may contain parameters such as plot runlength
      (primary and secondary), difference between primary and secondary
      derived azimuth, pulse amplitude, etc.
catalogue.title: Radar Plot Characteristics

catalogue.definition: Measurement of the received power.
catalogue.remark:
Notes:

    1. POWER is the measured value of the power received on the sum
       pattern for a plot.
    2. Negative values are expressed in 2's complement form, bit-8 is
       set to 0 for positive values and 1 for negative values.
catalogue.title: Received Power

catalogue.definition: Absolute time stamping expressed as Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) time.
catalogue.remark:
Notes:

    1. The exchange of this Data Item allows the easy derivation of the
       correct UTC time value, provided that the clocks at the data source
       and sink(s) are less than 512 seconds out of synchronisation.
       Special care has to be taken at the transition of an "all ones"
       value to an "all zeros" value (every 512 seconds).
    2. The time of day value is reset to 0 each day at midnight.
    3. For time management in radar transmission applications, refer to
       Part 1, paragraph 5.4 [Ref. 2].
catalogue.title: Truncated Time of Day

catalogue.definition: Presence of the X-Pulse for the various modes applied in the interrogation interlace pattern.
catalogue.remark:
Note:

    - This Data Item is transmitted only if at least one X-pulse has been
      received in a Mode-A, Mode-2 or Mode-C reply.
catalogue.title: Presence of X-Pulse

catalogue.definition: An integer value representing a unique reference to a track/plot record within a particular track/plot file.
catalogue.remark:
Note:

    - The differentiation between track and plot number is either implicit
      or is made via the Target Report Descriptor (Data Item I001/020).
catalogue.title: Track Plot Number

catalogue.definition: Status of track derived either from primary and/or secondary radar information.
catalogue.remark:
Notes:

    1. Bit-2 (GHO) is used to signal that the track is suspected to have
       been generated by a fake target.
    2. Bit-4 (RDPC) is used to signal the discontinuity of the track numbers.
catalogue.title: Track Status

catalogue.definition: Calculated track velocity expressed in polar co-ordinates.
catalogue.title: Calculated Track Velocity in Polar Co-ordinates

catalogue.definition: Relative track quality.
catalogue.remark:
Note:

    - Actual bit signification is application dependent.
catalogue.title: Track Quality

catalogue.definition: Special Purpose Field
catalogue.name: SP
catalogue.title: Special Purpose Field

catalogue.definition: Random Field Sequencing
catalogue.name: RFS
catalogue.title: Random Field Sequencing
